# Sharing your data

Nocturne gives you three ways to let someone else see your data, each built for
a different situation — a one-off clinic visit, an always-on screen at daycare,
or a person who needs their own ongoing login. This page explains what each one
does and when to reach for it.

You'll find all of these in your account under **Settings > Sharing & Privacy**.
Nothing is shared until you turn it on, and you can revoke any of it at any time.

## At a glance

| Option | Best for | Needs a login? | Expires |
|--------|----------|----------------|---------|
| Temporary guest link | A one-off look — a clinic visit | No | After 48 hours, one use |
| Public access link | An always-on screen — a daycare | No | Never (until you turn it off) |
| Member account | An ongoing helper — a teacher or nurse | Yes | Never (until you remove them) |

## Temporary guest link

A guest link gives someone a **read-only view of your data without an account**.
You create it, hand over the link (or the short code), and it lets them look —
they can't change anything. It **expires automatically after 48 hours** and can
only be used once, so there's nothing to remember to switch off afterwards.

You can revoke a guest link at any time before it's used, and once it's been
opened you can see when it was accessed and roughly from where. You can have a
handful of active guest links at once — one per person you're sharing with.

<Callout type="tip" title="When to use it: an endocrinologist's visit">
  You're seeing your endo on Tuesday and want them to look at your recent data on
  their own screen. Create a guest link labelled <strong>"Dr. Smith"</strong>,
  send it ahead of the appointment, and forget about it — it stops working on its
  own a couple of days later. No account to set up for a one-off visit, and
  nothing left switched on afterwards.
</Callout>

If you see the same clinician regularly, give them a **member account** with the
Clinician role instead, so they always have access without a new link each visit.

## Public access link

Public access turns on a single read-only link that **anyone you give it to can
open — with no login and no invite**. Because there's no sign-in, treat the link
itself as the key: anyone who has it can see whatever you've chosen to share.

You stay in control of two things:

- **What's visible.** Toggle individual categories on or off — blood glucose,
  statistics, treatments, device status, heart rate, step count, food, and
  reports. Everything you don't switch on stays private.
- **How far back.** Choose _All history_ or limit viewers to the _Last 24 hours_
  so older data is never exposed.

There's no expiry — the link works until you turn public access off. You can
**regenerate** it at any time, which instantly breaks the old link, and you can
see when it was last viewed.

<Callout type="tip" title="When to use it: a daycare">
  The daycare wants to keep your child's current glucose up on a tablet at the
  desk, and staff change shift through the day. Turn on public access, share
  <em>blood glucose</em> (and maybe <em>statistics</em>) only, and set the window
  to <em>Last 24 hours</em>. Everyone on shift sees the same screen with no logins
  to hand around, and they never see older history. If a device goes missing or
  the room changes, regenerate the link and the old one stops working.
</Callout>

<Callout type="warning" title="Anyone with the link can open it">
  There's no sign-in on a public link, and you can't control who it gets forwarded
  to once it's out. Share the minimum categories the setting actually needs, keep
  the 24-hour window on, and regenerate the link if you ever think it has spread
  too far.
</Callout>

## Member accounts & roles

For someone who needs ongoing access, invite them as a **member**. They get their
own login and you choose a **role** that decides what they can see and do. You
send an invite link (it expires in 7 days); they sign in or create an account to
accept, and from then on they have access until you change their role or remove
them.

Roles are the easiest way to set access. The common ones, from least to most
access:

| Role | What they can do |
|------|------------------|
| Viewer | See blood glucose and time-in-range statistics. Read-only — a quick glance. |
| Clinician | Read-only access across all data, including therapy settings and reports. For a doctor reviewing your numbers. |
| Caretaker | Everything a Clinician sees, plus the ability to log treatments and manage alerts. For someone who actively helps day to day. |
| Administrator | Full access to data and settings, including inviting and managing other people. For a co-parent or trusted manager. |
| Owner | You. Full control of the account; can't be removed. |

When you invite someone you can also tick **Only last 24 hours** to limit them to
recent data, the same way the public link works.

<Callout type="tip" title="When to use it: a teacher and a school nurse">
  At school, two people need access for the whole term, and they need different
  things. Invite the <strong>teacher as a Viewer</strong> — they just need to
  glance at the current glucose during class. Invite the
  <strong>school nurse as a Caretaker</strong>, so they can also log a treatment
  or manage an alert if they step in. Each has their own login, you can see them
  in your member list, and when the year ends you remove them in one click.
</Callout>

## Requesting access

Inviting someone is one direction — you reach out and hand them a link.
**Membership requests** are the other direction: you let people **ask you** for
access, and nothing is granted until you approve it.

Turn on **membership requests** under **Settings > Sharing & Privacy**, and
anyone who reaches your instance and signs in can send a request — optionally
with a short note saying who they are. This works whether or not public access
is on, and the request **never grants access on its own**; it waits in a queue.

You review requests under **Settings > Access Requests**: each one shows who
asked, their note, and when. Pick a role (plus any limits, like _Only last 24
hours_) and approve to add them as a member — or deny it. It's the same roles as
an invite; the only difference is who started the conversation.

<Callout type="tip" title="When to use it: a relative who wants to follow along">
  A grandparent asks to keep an eye on your child's glucose. Rather than
  collecting their email and sending an invite, switch membership requests on and
  point them at your instance. They sign in, request access, and you approve them
  as a <strong>Viewer</strong> when it suits you — or deny it if you change your
  mind.
</Callout>

## Which should I use?

- **One-off, short-lived look** (a single appointment) → **temporary guest link**.
  It cleans itself up after 48 hours.
- **A screen lots of people glance at** (a daycare, a classroom display) →
  **public access link**, with minimal categories and the 24-hour window.
- **A named person who needs ongoing access** (a regular clinician, a teacher, a
  nurse, a family member) → a **member account** with the right role.
- **Someone who should come to you** (you'd rather approve people than collect
  details and hand out links) → turn on **membership requests** and approve each
  one with the right role.

## Turning access back off

All three are reversible from **Settings > Sharing & Privacy**: revoke a guest
link, turn off (or regenerate) the public link, or change a member's role or
remove them entirely. Guest links also expire on their own. When in doubt, share
the least you can for the shortest time you can — you can always grant more later.
